<paragraph id="FE79CD20FFE1FFBBFCEE75C8DD6DFE8C" blockId="80.[869,1301,239,271]" box="[869,1301,239,271]" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">
<heading id="A5317A4CFFE1FFBBFCEE75C8DD6DFE8C" box="[869,1301,239,271]" centered="true" fontSize="12" level="2" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" reason="2">
3.9. 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFC1175C8DD6DFE8C" authority="BERNHAUER, 1915" authorityName="BERNHAUER" authorityYear="1915" box="[922,1301,239,271]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFC1175C8DC4BFE8C" box="[922,1075,239,271]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">Tetrabothrus</emphasis>
BERNHAUER, 1915
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B6DC9EABFFE1FFBBFCEE7416DC5BFC62" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FE79CD20FFE1FFBBFCEE7416DC1EFECC" blockId="80.[869,1126,305,335]" box="[869,1126,305,335]" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">
<heading id="A5317A4CFFE1FFBBFCEE7416DC1EFECC" box="[869,1126,305,335]" centered="true" fontSize="12" level="1" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" reason="5">3.9.1. General remarks</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE79CD20FFE1FFBBFCB4744EDC5BFC62" blockId="80.[831,1438,361,993]" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">
Including the new species described below and the newly proposed synonymies, 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFB1474AEDD5FFE22" authorityName="BERNHAUER" authorityYear="1915" box="[1183,1319,393,417]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFB1474AEDD5FFE22" box="[1183,1319,393,417]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">Tetrabothrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
currently includes 30 species (see checklist). The distribution of the genus ranges from the south of the East Palaearctic region (Himalaya, 
<collectingCountry id="86D18DB0FFE1FFBBFBA474CEDC0CFD82" box="[1071,1140,489,513]" name="China" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="86D18DB0FFE1FFBBFB0B74CEDCC7FD82" box="[1152,1215,489,513]" name="Japan" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">Japan</collectingCountry>
) across the Oriental into the Australian region. Some of the species (
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFAC3772DDB0DFDC2" authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canescens">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFAC3772DDB0DFDC2" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">T. canescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFC12770DDC3FFDC2" authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="2012" box="[921,1095,554,577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neoguineensis">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFC12770DDC3FFDC2" box="[921,1095,554,577]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">T. neoguineensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFBE0770DDC96FDC2" authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="2000" box="[1131,1262,554,577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="papuanus">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFBE0770DDC96FDC2" box="[1131,1262,554,577]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">T. papuanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFA99770DDDEEFDC2" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1915" box="[1298,1430,553,577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFA99770DDDEEFDC2" box="[1298,1430,553,577]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">T. pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFCB4776DDBB3FDE2" box="[831,971,585,609]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semialatus">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFCB4776DDBB3FDE2" box="[831,971,585,609]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">T. semialatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) are of doubtful identity, as their descriptions are based on females; a reliable identification of most 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFCF677AEDC21FD22" box="[893,1113,649,673]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFCF677AEDC7DFD22" box="[893,1029,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">Tetrabothrus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
is possible only based on the morphology of the aedeagus. Several taxa are currently known only from their respective 
<typeStatus id="217D7382FFE1FFBBFB3377EDDC9FFD61" box="[1208,1255,714,738]" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">type</typeStatus>
localities. Based on available zoogeographic data, some species appear to have restricted distributions, whereas others are remarkably widespread. The latter is especially true of 
<taxonomicName id="39C6B6A3FFE1FFBBFCB4766DDBC8FCE2" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1915" box="[831,944,841,865]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Tetrabothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="80" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis id="CCB21132FFE1FFBBFCB4766DDBC8FCE2" box="[831,944,841,865]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">T. clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is distributed in most of the south of the East Palaearctic and across the Oriental regions. This species appears to be present also in the Australian region (New 
<collectingCountry id="86D18DB0FFE1FFBBFC59768EDC5BFC42" box="[978,1059,937,961]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">Guinea</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="86D18DB0FFE1FFBBFBBB768EDCEFFC42" box="[1072,1175,937,961]" name="Australia" pageId="80" pageNumber="93">Australia</collectingCountry>
), but only females have been recorded so far.
</paragraph>
